cluster_relations.rel_desc: Accountability is presented as an example of an ethical dilemma in AI development.

args.canonical_rel_desc: The subject is a specific example or member of the broader category represented by the object.
args.justification: Both relations describe a concrete example (story specifics of the Hook Man legend; accountability) being treated as an instance of a broader conceptual category (urban legends; ethical dilemmas in AI development).
These links express a type–instance / exemplar–category relationship, where the subject is categorized under the object.
Type–instance relations are a form of identity/categorization, tying a specific instance to its conceptual identity within a category.

args.canonical_rel_desc: The subject is a specific problematic condition or state that the object can be in.
args.justification: The description frames incomplete data as a problematic form or state of training data, emphasizing a particular negative condition rather than a simple type-instance category.
args.remark: Chosen to distinguish problematic states (like incompleteness) from neutral type-instance links.

args.justification: The relation captures a quality-related defect (incompleteness) of training data, fitting a family of data quality and defect relations.
The link concerns the quality state of the training data (a problematic quality/condition) rather than composition, causality, or pure identity.
